channel.description:
Not sure if many of you use irc, if you don't, start using it now. There's 1000x more action going on than on these forums. Irc bots are bots that can manage a channel, you can play games with others if you have a gamebot and of course you can make bots that spam channels + much more like botnets and stuff but now I'm gonna show you how to make an irc bot. Let's begin.

First, import these [code]import java.net.*;
import java.lang.*;
import java.io.*;
import java.*;
import java.util.*;[/code]Quick explanation of those packages.
java.lang = has classes that are the base of java's design
java.net = apps that connect to something/where need this since it handles all the connection stuff.
java.io = input and output datastreams and stuff
java.util = used with time and stuff like if you want to make a clock you'd do [new java.util.Date();]
Ok. Done importing? Great.

Add this below what you just added [code]public class MoparscapeBOT {

	static String USER = "userhere";//bots nick
	static String PASS = "passhere";//bots password
	static String CHAN = "#channel";//the channel you want the bot to join
	static boolean pass = true;
	static boolean chan = true;
	static boolean connected;[/code]This is the main class of your bot where you set it's name, password and the channel it joins on connection. 
After doing that, add this [code]	static Socket mainSock;
	static BufferedReader inComing;
	static BufferedWriter outGoing;[/code]socket is used to create connection between you and the server, the readers below are for reading incoming/outgoing stuff. 

Next, add this [code]	public static void main(String bot[]) {
		System.out.println("Starting bot...");
		BotMain main = new BotMain();
		main.connect("irc.freenode.net", 6667);
                System.out.println("Connected to server!");
	}[/code]Here is where you set the irc server you're connecting to, so set it to the one that you're going to use. I used freenode as an example, 6667 is the port and most irc servers use 6667.

Almost done, add this now. [code]	public static void connect(String ip, int port) {
		try {
		mainSock = new Socket(ip, port);
		outGoing = new BufferedWriter(new OutputStreamWriter(mainSock.getOutputStream()));
		inComing = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(mainSock.getInputStream()));
		outGoing.write("USER " + USER + " 8 * " + USER + "\n");
			if (pass)
		//		outGoing.write("PASS " + PASS + "\n");
				outGoing.write("NICK " + USER + "\n");
			if (chan)
				outGoing.write("JOIN " + CHAN + "\n");
				outGoing.write("MODE " + USER + " :+i\n");
				outGoing.write("MODE " + USER + " :-f\n");
				outGoing.flush();
				String inComingData = null;
					while((inComingData = inComing.readLine()) != null) {
						if (inComingData.contains("PING")) {
							outGoing.write("PING");
						}
					}
				connected = true;
			} catch (Exception deathLol) {
				connected = false;
				System.out.println("omg...couldnt connect...omg...");
			}

		}
}
[/code]This is where it actually connects, first it tries to create a socket with the server you set, right now to freenode. Then if your bot is registered, it identifies itself with the server so that it's name won't get changed.
[code]						if (inComingData.contains("PING")) {
							outGoing.write("PING");[/code] is for checking that if someone pings the bot, it won't crash, instead, it will reply to the ping.


